    <div class="section">
      <h2>Historical Background</h2>
      <p>
        The Taj Mahal, commissioned by Emperor Shah Jahan in 1632, was built as a mausoleum for his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal. Completed in 1653, it stands as a symbol of Mughal opulence and love, blending Persian, Islamic, and Indian architectural elements. The monument was designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983.<br>
        <em>References: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taj_Mahal" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a></em>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <h2>Architecture</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Symmetrical design, central dome (70 m high), four minarets (40 m each)</li>
        <li>Main mausoleum, mosque, guest house, and charbagh garden</li>
        <li>White marble and intricate inlays reflect Persian and Islamic influences</li>
        <li>Key features: iwans, pishtaqs, and reflection pool</li>
      </ul>
      <img 
        src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/39/Interior_of_the_Taj_Mahal_01.jpg"
        alt="Taj Mahal Interior"
        class="taj-detail"
        loading="lazy"
      >
      <em>References: <a href="https://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/shades-of-the-past/article5404569.ece" target="_blank">The Hindu</a></em>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <h2>Building Materials & Properties</h2>
      <table class="materials-table">
        <tr>
          <th>Material</th>
          <th>Use</th>
          <th>Properties</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Makrana Marble</td>
          <td>Main mausoleum, dome, decorative elements</td>
          <td>High strength (~70 MPa), low porosity, brilliant white, durable</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Red Sandstone</td>
          <td>Plinths, mosque, guest house</td>
          <td>Strong, easy to carve, visually striking</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Lime-Surkhi Mortar</td>
          <td>Binding masonry</td>
          <td>Moderate hydraulicity, high porosity, enhanced with organic additives</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <p>
        <em>References: <a href="https://www.constructionandbuildingresearch.com/" target="_blank">CE & CR, 2021</a></em>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <h2>Builder’s Thought Process</h2>
      <p>
        Shah Jahan sought an eternal monument to love, prioritizing aesthetic perfection and symmetry. The use of Makrana marble ensured visual splendor, while lime-surkhi mortar provided resilience in Agra’s humid climate. Organic additives, as described in the <em>Brihat Samhita</em>, enhanced durability and reduced cracking.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <h2>Structural Design & Current Condition</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Load-bearing masonry with a central dome supported by thick walls and arches</li>
        <li>Minarets slightly tilted outward for earthquake safety</li>
        <li>Well-preserved due to marble’s durability and ongoing ASI conservation</li>
        <li>Challenges: Pollution-related discoloration, minor cracks addressed with lime-based repairs</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <em>Reference: <a href="http://architecturalheritage.intach.org/" target="_blank">INTACH Heritage at Risk Register</a></em>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <h2>Comparison: Taj Mahal vs RCC Structures</h2>
      <table class="compare-table">
        <tr>
          <th></th>
          <th>Taj Mahal (Lime Masonry)</th>
          <th>Modern RCC</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Breathability</td>
          <td>High (prevents moisture damage)</td>
          <td>Low (can trap moisture, cause cracks)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Compressive Strength</td>
          <td>~10 MPa (mortar), ~70 MPa (marble)</td>
          <td>20–50 MPa (concrete)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Durability</td>
          <td>Centuries (with maintenance)</td>
          <td>50–100 years</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Repair</td>
          <td>Compatible, reversible</td>
          <td>Challenging, often irreversible</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </div>

